// Switch Statement 
A switch statement is a selection statement that evaluates an expression and executes the block of code associated
with the first matching case. If no case matches, the optional default block is executed.
A switch statement is used instead of multiple independent if-else-if comparisons when all the conditions are 
checking the same variable against fixed values.
but
There are many situations where if-else-if is better than switch.
========================================= Rule of Thumb =======================================================
Use switch when:
You are comparing ONE variable against MANY FIXED VALUES.
Example:
int month = 3;
switch (month)
{
    case 1:
        Console.WriteLine("January");
        break;

    case 2:
        Console.WriteLine("February");
        break;

    case 3:
        Console.WriteLine("March");
        break;
}
Perfect use case.
Use if-else-if when:

1. You have ranges
int marks = 82;
if (marks >= 90)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Grade A");
}
else if (marks >= 75)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Grade B");
}
else if (marks >= 60)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Grade C");
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("Fail");
}
Can you write this using a basic switch?
❌ No.

2. Multiple variables are involved
if (age >= 18 && hasLicense)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Can Drive");
}
Here you're checking
age
hasLicense
A basic switch works with one expression, not arbitrary Boolean logic.

3. Complex Boolean expressions
if ((salary > 50000 && experience > 5) || isManager)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Eligible");
}
Again,
❌ A normal switch isn't a natural fit.

4. Different variables in different conditions
if (age > 18)
{
}
else if (salary > 50000)
{
}
else if (country == "India")
{
}
Notice every condition is different.
A switch cannot naturally express this.
When switch is clearly better ?
Suppose you're building a calculator.
char op = '+';

Using if ..
if (op == '+')
{
}
else if (op == '-')
{
}
else if (op == '*')
{
}
else if (op == '/')
{
}

Using switch ..
switch (op)
{
    case '+':
        break;

    case '-':
        break;

    case '*':
        break;

    case '/':
        break;
}
The switch version is:
Cleaner
Easier to read
Easier to maintain.

Real-world examples
Example 1 – Login Role
switch(role)
{
    case "Admin":
        ...
        break;

    case "User":
        ...
        break;

    case "Guest":
        ...
        break;
}
Perfect for switch.

Example 2 – Tax Calculation
if (income <= 300000)
{
}
else if (income <= 700000)
{
}
else if (income <= 1200000)
{
}
Perfect for if-else-if.

Note : 
switch gives the compiler an opportunity to optimize the decision-making process. Depending on the number and 
pattern of case values, the compiler may use a jump table, a lookup table, or a sequence of comparisons. 
Therefore, switch is often—but not always—more efficient than a long if-else-if chain.

For example :
If you have
switch(day)
{
    case 1:
    case 2:
    case 3:
    case 4:
}
the compiler may generate something like a jump table.

But suppose your cases are :
case 1:
case 2:
case 100:
case 1000:
case 100000:
A jump table would waste a huge amount of memory.
So the compiler may instead generate comparisons internally.

Because :
Instead of
1
2
3
4

The compiler would have to make
1 ✔
2 ✔
3 ✘
4 ✘
5 ✘
6 ✘
7 ✘
...
99 ✘
100 ✔
101 ✘
...
1000 ✔
...
100000 ✔

Almost every slot is empty.
How much memory?
Suppose each entry uses only 8 bytes.
A jump table for
100000 entries
would need roughly
100000 × 8
=
800000 bytes
≈ 781 KB

Just to represent 5 cases.
That is a huge waste.

Note : -
Modern C# supports switching on many types, including:
int
char
string
enum

Also :
Every case in a C# switch must end with:
✔ break;
✔ return;
✔ throw;
✔ goto case;
✔ goto default;
even in C# this appliles to default (used in case of no match) as well , unlike C or C++ .

// Jump statement in C#
A jump statement is a statement that immediately transfers program control from one location to another, 
altering the normal sequential flow of execution.

1. break : The break statement immediately terminates the nearest enclosing loop or switch statement and 
transfers control to the statement following it.
Example :
for(int i = 1; i <= 10; i++)
{
    if(i == 5)
        break;
    Console.WriteLine(i);
}
Output :
1
2
3
4
Control jumps outside the loop.

2. continue : The continue statement skips the remaining statements in the current iteration and immediately 
starts the next iteration of the loop.
Example :
for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++)
{
    if(i == 3)
        continue;
    Console.WriteLine(i);
}
Output :
1
2
4
5
Only the current iteration is skipped.

3. return : The return statement immediately terminates the current method and optionally returns a value 
to the caller.
Example :
static int Add()
{
    return 10 + 20;
}
The method ends immediately after return.

4. goto : The goto statement transfers control directly to a labeled statement or another case within a switch 
statement.
Example :

goto Start;
Console.WriteLine("Hello");
Start:
Console.WriteLine("Welcome");

Output :
Welcome
Execution jumps directly to the label.

5. throw : 
The throw statement throws an exception and immediately transfers control to the nearest matching exception handler.
Example :
throw new Exception("Invalid Input");
The program stops normal execution and looks for a catch block.

Note : - Most professional C# developers avoid goto because it can make code harder to read and maintain, 
though it has a few legitimate uses (especially goto case inside a switch).

Example :
int number = 10;
switch (number)
{
    case 1:
        Console.WriteLine("One");
        break;

    case 10:
        goto default;

    default:
        Console.WriteLine("Unknown Number");
        break;
}
You can use goto for normal case as well as default .

// rest staements are given below ..
1. Checked / Unchecked Statements : checked and unchecked statements control whether arithmetic overflow is 
detected during integral-type calculations.
Why do we need them?
Suppose a byte can store only 0–255.
byte a = 255;
byte b = 1;
What should happen when we add them?
255 + 1 = 256
A byte cannot store 256.
Should the program:
Throw an error? ✅ (checked)
Ignore it and wrap around? ✅ (unchecked)
That's what these statements control.
Example :
checked
{
    byte a = 255;
    byte b = 1;
    byte c = (byte)(a + b);   // OverflowException
}
unchecked
{
    byte a = 255;
    byte b = 1;
    byte c = (byte)(a + b);

    Console.WriteLine(c);
}
Output :
0

2. Lock Statement : The lock statement ensures that only one thread at a time can execute a critical section of code.
Why do we need it?
Imagine two users transferring money from the same bank account at the exact same time.
Without lock:
Balance = 10000
User A withdraws 5000
User B withdraws 7000
↓
Final Balance becomes incorrect

With lock :
User A finishes
↓
User B starts
Example :
lock(balanceLock)
{
    balance -= amount;
}

3. Using Statement : The using statement automatically disposes objects that use unmanaged resources after 
their work is complete.
Why?
Suppose you open a file. If you forget to close it, memory stays occupied file remains locked Instead
using(StreamReader reader = new StreamReader("data.txt"))
{
    Console.WriteLine(reader.ReadToEnd());
}
After the block finishes,
reader.Dispose();
is called automatically.
Very common with:
Files
Database Connections
Network Streams


4. Yield Statement : The yield statement returns elements one at a time from an iterator instead of returning 
the entire collection at once.
Don't worry if this sounds confusing—it usually clicks after you learn collections and iterators.
Normal Method :
return list;
Everything is returned at once.

with Yield :
yield return 1;
yield return 2;
yield return 3;

The values come one by one.
Example :
public static IEnumerable<int> Numbers()
{
    yield return 1;
    yield return 2;
    yield return 3;
}
Usage :
foreach(var n in Numbers())
{
    Console.WriteLine(n);
}
Output
1
2
3
5.

Empty Statement : An empty statement is a statement that performs no action. It is represented by a single semicolon (;).
Example :
;
Yes...
This is actually a valid statement.

Another example :
while(Console.ReadLine() != "exit")
{
}
or
while(Console.ReadLine() != "exit");
Here the semicolon means
Do nothing  until the condition becomes false.


Exception Handling Statements : 
Exception handling statements are statements used to detect, handle, and recover from runtime errors so that the 
program can continue executing normally instead of terminating unexpectedly.

Why do we need Exception Handling?
Suppose your program asks the user for age.
Console.Write("Enter Age: ");
int age = Convert.ToInt32(Console.ReadLine());
User enters:
Piyush
Instead of
25
What happens?
Without exception handling
Program Starts
↓
User enters "Piyush"
↓
FormatException
↓
Program Crashes ❌

Imagine this in.....
Banking software
Hospital software
Railway reservation
A crash is unacceptable 😁 users can play.


With Exception Handling ....
Program Starts
↓
User enters wrong input
↓
Handle Error
↓
Show Friendly Message
↓
Program Continues